00042 SgAsmGenericFile *
00043 SgAsmExecutableFileFormat::parseBinaryFormat(const char *name)
00044 {
00045     SgAsmGenericFile *ef=NULL;
00046     std::vector<DataConverter*> converters;
00047     converters.push_back(NULL); /*no conversion*/
00048     converters.push_back(new Rot13);
00049 
00050     try {
00051         for (size_t ci=0; !ef && ci<converters.size(); ci++) {
00052             ef = new SgAsmGenericFile();
00053             ef->set_data_converter(converters[ci]);
00054             converters[ci] = NULL;
00055             ef->parse(name);
00056 
00057             if (SgAsmElfFileHeader::is_ELF(ef)) {
00058                 (new SgAsmElfFileHeader(ef))->parse();
00059             } else if (SgAsmDOSFileHeader::is_DOS(ef)) {
00060                 SgAsmDOSFileHeader *dos_hdr = new SgAsmDOSFileHeader(ef);
00061                 dos_hdr->parse(false); /*delay parsing the DOS Real Mode Section*/
00062 
00063                 /* DOS Files can be overloaded to also be PE, NE, LE, or LX. Such files have an Extended DOS Header
00064                  * immediately after the DOS File Header (various forms of Extended DOS Header exist). The Extended DOS Header
00065                  * contains a file offset to a PE, NE, LE, or LX File Header, the first bytes of which are a magic number. The
00066                  * is_* methods check for this magic number. */
00067                 SgAsmGenericHeader *big_hdr = NULL;
00068                 if (SgAsmPEFileHeader::is_PE(ef)) {
00069                     SgAsmDOSExtendedHeader *dos2_hdr = new SgAsmDOSExtendedHeader(dos_hdr);
00070                     dos2_hdr->parse();
00071                     SgAsmPEFileHeader *pe_hdr = new SgAsmPEFileHeader(ef);
00072                     pe_hdr->set_offset(dos2_hdr->get_e_lfanew());
00073                     pe_hdr->parse();
00074                     big_hdr = pe_hdr;
00075                 } else if (SgAsmNEFileHeader::is_NE(ef)) {
00076                     SgAsmNEFileHeader::parse(dos_hdr);
00077                 } else if (SgAsmLEFileHeader::is_LE(ef)) { /*or LX*/
00078                     SgAsmLEFileHeader::parse(dos_hdr);
00079                 }
00080 
00081 #if 0 /*This iterferes with disassembling the DOS interpretation*/
00082                 /* Now go back and add the DOS Real-Mode section but rather than using the size specified in the DOS header,
00083                  * constrain it to not extend beyond the beginning of the PE, NE, LE, or LX file header. This makes detecting
00084                  * holes in the PE format much easier. */
00085                 dos_hdr->parse_rm_section(big_hdr ? big_hdr->get_offset() : 0);
00086 #else
00087                 dos_hdr->parse_rm_section(0);
00088 #endif
00089             } else {
00090                 if (ef) delete ef->get_data_converter();
00091                 SageInterface::deleteAST(ef);      /* ~SgAsmGenericFile() closes ef->p_fd if it was opened. */
00092                 ef = NULL;
00093             }
00094         }
00095     } catch(...) {
00096         for (size_t ci=0; ci<converters.size(); ci++)
00097             delete converters[ci];
00098         if (ef) delete ef->get_data_converter();
00099         SageInterface::deleteAST(ef);
00100         ef = NULL;
00101         throw;
00102     }
00103     
00104     /* If no executable file could be parsed then try to use system tools to get the file type. On Unix-based systems, the
00105      * "file" command does a thorough job of trying to figure out the type of file. If we can't figure out the file name then
00106      * just throw some generic error. */
00107     if (!ef) {
00108         /* Use file(1) to try to figure out the file type to report in the exception */
00109         int child_stdout[2];
00110 #ifdef _MSC_VER
00111 #pragma message ("WARNING: Commented out use of functions from sys/wait.h")
00112                 printf ("ERROR: Commented out use of functions from sys/wait.h \n");
00113                 ROSE_ASSERT(false);
00114 #else
00115                 pipe(child_stdout);
00116         pid_t pid = fork();
00117         if (0==pid) {
00118             close(0);
00119             dup2(child_stdout[1], 1);
00120             close(child_stdout[0]);
00121             close(child_stdout[1]);
00122             execlp("file", "file", "-b", name, NULL);
00123             exit(1);
00124         } else if (pid>0) {
00125             char buf[4096];
00126             memset(buf, 0, sizeof buf);
00127             read(child_stdout[0], buf, sizeof buf);
00128             buf[sizeof(buf)-1] = '\0';
00129             if (char *nl = strchr(buf, '\n')) *nl = '\0'; /*keep only first line w/o LF*/
00130             waitpid(pid, NULL, 0);
00131             char mesg[64+sizeof buf];
00132             sprintf(mesg, "unrecognized file format: %s", buf);
00133             throw FormatError(mesg);
00134         } else {
00135             throw FormatError("unrecognized file format");
00136         }
00137 #endif
00138     }
00139 
00140     ef->set_tracking_references(false); /*all done parsing*/
00141 
00142     /* Is the file large enough to hold all sections?  If any section extends past the EOF then set truncate_zeros, which will
00143      * cause the unparser to not write zero bytes to the end of the file. */
00144     ef->set_truncate_zeros(ef->get_current_size()>ef->get_orig_size());
00145 
00146     /* If any section is the target of a function symbol then mark that section as containing code even if that section is not
00147      * memory mapped with execute permission. */
00148 
00149 #ifndef USE_ROSE
00150  // DQ (1/27/2010): This is a problem for ROSE compiling this file.
00151     struct: public AstSimpleProcessing {
00152         void visit(SgNode *node) {
00153             SgAsmGenericSymbol *symbol = isSgAsmGenericSymbol(node);
00154             if (symbol && symbol->get_type()==SgAsmGenericSymbol::SYM_FUNC) {
00155                 SgAsmGenericSection *section = symbol->get_bound();
00156                 if (section)
00157                     section->set_contains_code(true);
00158             }
00159         }
00160     } t1;
00161     t1.traverse(ef, preorder);
00162 #endif
00163 
00164     return ef;
00165 }

00171 std::string SgAsmExecutableFileFormat::isa_family_to_string(SgAsmExecutableFileFormat::InsSetArchitecture isa)
00172 {
00173   switch(isa & ISA_FAMILY_MASK){
00174     case ISA_IA32_Family:  return "Intel x86";     /* x86 IA-32 family of architectures; Intel, AMD, VIA, ... */
00175     case ISA_X8664_Family: return "x86-64";        /* x86-64 family of architectures: Intel, AMD, VIA, ... */
00176     case ISA_SPARC_Family: return "SPARC";         /* SPARC family of architectures; Sun Microsystems */
00177     case ISA_M68K_Family:  return "Motorola m68k"; /* Motorala m68k family */
00178     case ISA_M88K_Family:  return "Motorola m88k"; /* Motorola m88k family (not very popular) */
00179     case ISA_MIPS_Family:  return "MIPS";          /* 32/64-bit RISC; MIPS Technologies, Inc. */
00180     case ISA_I860_Family:  return "Intel i860";    /* Intel i860 family; 1989-mid 90's; RISC VLIW */
00181     case ISA_IA64_Family:  return "Itanium";       /* Intel 64-bit architecture */
00182     case ISA_ARM_Family:   return "ARM";           /* Acorn RISC Machine, Advanced RISC Machines, ARM Limited */
00183     case ISA_OTHER_Family: 
00184       switch(isa){
00185         case ISA_PowerPC:
00186         case ISA_PowerPC_64bit: return "PowerPC"; 
00187         default:
00188           return "Other Family";
00189       };
00190     default:
00191       break;
00192   };
00193   char buf[64];
00194   snprintf(buf,sizeof(buf),"unknown isa family (%zu)",size_t(isa & ISA_FAMILY_MASK)) ;
00195   return buf;
00196 }
